Source: Panafrican News Agency (Dakar) 2 May 2001 [edited
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200105020009.html>

Ebola Virus Antibody Detected in Kenyan Monkeys
-----------------------------------------------
NAIROBI: Barely a fortnight after medical authorities ruled out the
presence of Ebola hemorrhagic fever in Kenya, scientists now say the
country is home to primates carrying the Ebola virus. Dr. Walter Ochieng, a
scientist working with the Centre for Viral Research at the Kenya Medical
Research Institute (KEMRI), has said that [signs of Ebola virus were
recently [detected in some monkeys in the Kakamega and Mount Elgon forests
of western Kenya. Ochieng told the Kenya Medical Association Annual
Conference that virologists at KEMRI had stumbled on antibodies in [random
samples collected from monkeys in the 2 forests.
More research should be done on the subject, Ochieng said, though he was
"unhappy" that, despite the availability of competent researchers, vital
scientific studies were hampered by lack of funds. Though researchers have
yet to establish how animal viral diseases like Ebola spread to humans,
Ochieng said effective preventive and curative measures would be put in
place only when the mode of transmission was discovered.
A fortnight ago a female recruit at the Kenya Police Academy at Nyeri in
central Kenya succumbed to a high fever, headache, and bleeding through all
body openings, symptoms of Ebola [and other hemorrhagic fevers. Her death,
and the hospitalization of another recruit at the same academy exhibiting
similar symptoms, sent shock-waves throughout the country as medical
specialists grappled with the problem. Health authorities later ruled out
Ebola hemorrhagic fever as the cause of death, explaining that [the female
patient had died from a blood disorder-related ailment, while the other
trainee had been diagnosed as suffering from typhoid fever. In late 2000,
an Ebola outbreak in neighboring Uganda caused panic and forced Kenyan
authorities to send screening teams to all border posts between the 2
countries. A number of Kenyans who attended funerals of their relatives in
Uganda were quarantined for over a week at Busia border point.
