[Ebola virus is a negative-stranded RNA virus classified together with
Marburg virus in the family _Filoviridae_. All known filoviruses appear to
be highly pathogenic for non-human primates. Outbreaks of filovirus disease
have occurred in Europe and North America in monkeys imported from Africa
and the Philippines, sometimes with spread of infection to humans. Contact
with the tissues of dead non-human primates was a source of infection for
humans on at least 2 occasions in Africa.
Nevertheless, the lethality of the viruses for non-human primates suggests
that, like humans, non-human primates are incidental victims of infection
and are not true reservoir hosts. The source of filoviruses in nature
remains unknown, but in some instances, bats roosted in buildings or a cave
visited or frequented by people who subsequently were found to have primary
cases of infection in outbreaks of disease in Africa; one patient was
bitten or stung by what is presumed to have been an arthropod 7 days before
coming down with Marburg disease. For further discussion of this subject
see the article by R. Swanepoel et al., published in Emerging Infectious
Diseases, vol. 2, no. 2, Oct-Dec, 1996
(<http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/eid/vol2no4/swanepo2.htm>). - Mod.CP
